  content obj_root_law_sections_5_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_5_footnotes
  sourcePage 5
obj_root_law_sections_5_content:
  string
  line 5
  line `by any other evidence procurable, whether in favor of Government o r of the claimants, and decisions shall`
  line `then be passed on them as to the continuance, resumption, or full or partial assessment of the lands.`
  line `10. In cases where the notices provided for in Sections V. and VII. fail to procure the attendance of the`
  line `persons to whom they are addressed, and no claimant appears to prosecute his claim, the Commissioner or`
  line `Assistant Commissioner shall proceed to ascertain the facts of the case from such evidence as may he`
  line `forthcoming or procurable, and shall pronounce such decisio n thereupon as to him shall seem just regarding`
  line `the lands or interests to which the notices referred.`
  line `11. An attachment enforced under Rule 8 shall be removed by the Collector or Chief Revenue Authority`
  line `by whom it was made, on receipt of a communication fr om the Inam Commissioner or his Assistant,`
  line `certifying that he considers the attachment to be no longer necessary; but the rents collected from the land`
  line `during its attachment shall in no case be restored to the alleged proprietor, except under the general o r`
  line `special instructions of Government.`
  line `12. Certified copies of decisions, made according to the provisions of Rule 9, shall be delivered as soon`
  line `as possible after each decision is passed, to the persons on whose claims the decision shall have been`
  line `pronounce d, or their agents; and copies of all decisions made in the absence of any claimant, according to`
  line `the provisions of Rule 10, shall he sent to the Mamlutdar, or other Revenue manager of the talook in which`
  line `the lands to which they relate are situated, who sh all deliver them to the parties affected by them, should`
  line `they be discoverable, or otherwise cause them to be publicly posted in the village to which the lands in`
  line `question belong.`
  line `13. Decisions, affecting any lands or any interests therein, passed under thi s enactment, shall be carried`
  line `into execution by the Collector or Chief Revenue Authority of the District in which the lands to which they`
  line `relate are situated, at the requisition of the Inam Commissioner or his Assistant, in any manner which may,`
  line `from time to time, be prescribed by the Governor of Bombay in Council.`
  line `14. In all cases where a person may be desirous of appealing against any decision of the Inam`
  line `Commissioner or his Assistants, he shall apply by a petition, addressed to the Authority by whom, acc ording`
  line `to Rule 2, his appeal is cognizable, which petition shall be presented to such Authority within one hundred`
  line `days from the date of the decree appealed against, a copy of which must accompany the petition of appeal,`
  line `and no appeal which is not so made shall be admitted, without proof of the existence of a just and necessary`
  line `cause for its not having been preferred in due time; and it is hereby provided, that no decree passed by the`
  line `Inam Commissioner or any of his Assistants, shall be liable to be set asi de for want of form in the`
  line `proceedings, but only for matters affecting the justice of the decision.`
  line `SCHEDULE B`
  line `Rules for the adjudication of titles to estates claimed as I nam or exempt from payment of land`
  line revenue
  line `1. Regarding Inams already declared permanent by competent authority since the introduction`
  line `of the present Government. — All lands held under a specific and absolute declaration by the British`
  line `Government, or any competent officer acting under it, that they were to be continued hereditarily or in`
  line `perpetuity exempt, wholly or partially, from the payment of Revenue, are to be so continued according t o`
  line `the purport of such declaration.`
  line `Provision 1 st. — If any question shall arise as to the competency of the officer to make or give such`
  line `declaration as aforesaid, the Commissioner or Assistant Commissioner is to suspend his judgment, and`
  line `report the circumsta nces of the case to the Governor of Bombay in Council, to whom a power is hereby`
  line `reserved of determining finally whether such officer was competent to make or give such declaration, and`
  line `the Commissioner or Assistant Commissioner, upon receiving the determi nation of the said Governor in`
  line `Council, shall decide accordingly.`
obj_root_law_sections_5_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_6:
  kind page
  sectionId pdf-page-6
  sectionNo (6)
  orderNo 6
  title `Page 6`
  content obj_root_law_sections_6_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_6_footnotes
  sourcePage 6
obj_root_law_sections_6_content:
  string
  line 6
  line `2. Regarding claims to per sonal Inams, not yet adjudicated under the present Government. —`
  line `Any land held under a sunnud declaring it to be hereditary, shall be so continued according to the t erms of`
  line `the sunnud.`
  line `Provision 1 st. — Provided that the grant was either made, or specifically recognized, by Authority`
  line `competent to alienate Government Revenue in perpetuity, the question of which recognition and`
  line `competency is to be referred to and determine d by Government in the manner prescribed by Provision 1 st,`
  line `Rule 1.`
  line `Provision 2 nd. — And provided that there be nothing in the conditions of the tenure which cannot be`
  line `observed without a breach of the laws of the land, or the rules of public decency.`
  line `Provision 3 rd. — And provided that the grant was not afterwards revoked or disallowed, or an alteration`
  line `of its terms ordered or recognized by a competent authority.`
  line `3. All lands uninterruptedly held as wholly or partially exempt from assessment for a period of sixty`
  line `years before the introduction of the British Government, and then in the authorized possession of a grandson`
  line `in male descent, or male heir of the body of such grandson of the original grantee, shall continue to be so`
  line `held so long as there shall be in existence any male heir of the body of the person who was incumbent at`
  line `the introduction of the British Government, tracing his lineage from such incumbent through male heirs`
  line only.
  line `4. All lands, uninterruptedly held as wholly or partially exempt from as sessment, for a period of forty`
  line `years before the introduction of the British Government, and then in the authorized possession of a son, or`
  line `male heir of the body of a son of the original grantee, are to be continued for one succession further than`
  line `that of the person who was incumbent at the introduction of the British Government, that is, until the death`
  line `of his last surviving son.`
  line `Provision 1 st. — The authorized possession contemplated by Rules 8 and 4 does not involve the`
  line `necessity of proving any specific authority from, or recognition by, the Government or Paramount Power.`
  line `The mere entry of the holding, as continued in the genuine accounts of the District Officers (even in those`
  line `not audited and passed by the Government of the time being), will be sufficien t to bring it under the heads`
  line `of “uninterrupted” and “authorized” so far as regards the purposes of this Rule; provided only that there are`
  line `no entries in the Collectorate accounts, which shew that the holding of such lands exempt as aforesaid must`
  line `have bee n unauthorized by the Government or Paramount Power.`
  line `Provision 2 nd. — If there be not evidence forthcoming to disprove a claimant's assertion that his holding`
  line `has been undisputedly enjoyed for the number of years and descents requisite to fulfil the conditio ns of`
  line `Rules 3 and 4 respectively, his prescriptive right shall be admitted.`
  line `Provision 3 rd. — The introduction of the British Government is to be reckoned from the time the East`
  line `India Company became the Government or Paramount Authority over each District as regards its Inams. In`
  line `the Territories ceded by or conquered from the Peshwa, therefore, whether Khalsat Mahals or Serinjams,`
  line `&c., held exclusive of Inams, &c., the introduction of the British Government will date from the close of`
  line `that of the Peshwa. But i n case of the lapse of an independent principality, or of a jagheer more ancient than`
  line `the Peshwa's Government, and over the Inams of which he did not claim any authority, the introduction of`
  line `the British Government should be reckoned only from the date at w hich the general management of the`
  line `Districts may have come into the hands of the Company, and in case any question shall arise as to the`
  line `precise date when the East India Company became the Government over any district, or when the general`
  line `management of any District came into their hands, such question shall be referred to and determined by`
  line `Government in the manner prescribed by Provision 1 st, Rule 1.`
  line `6. Land held as wholly exempt from payment of Revenue, or on partial assessment, the possession of`
  line `which is not continuable under the preceding Rules, is to be resumed on the demise of the incumbent.`
obj_root_law_sections_6_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_7:
  kind page
  sectionId pdf-page-7
  sectionNo (7)
  orderNo 7
  title `Page 7`
  content obj_root_law_sections_7_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_7_footnotes
  sourcePage 7
obj_root_law_sections_7_content:
  string
  line 7
  line `Provision 1 st. — In case the incumbent at the time of the introduction of the British Government may`
  line `have died, the permission to hold for life is to be extended to t he person in whose name the land may be`
  line `continued, when the investigation is commenced, if there be no fraud apparent, nor other reason for`
  line `withholding this indulgence.`
  line `Provision 2 nd. — When land is evidently held by fraud recently committed, (as when an Ina m which`
  line `was resumed under the late Government has been re - occupied under the present Government without`
  line `authority, of as when a pretended Inam is found to have originated. Since the introduction of this`
  line `Government with the connivance of District or Village Officers), it shall be at once resumed, not being`
  line `continuable under this or any of the preceding Rules.`
  line `7. Regarding claims to Inams apparently permanent by the nature of the objects for which they`
  line `are held, and not merely personal. — All lands held for the support of Mosques, Temples, or similar`
  line `Institutions, of the permanent character of which there can be no doubt, are to be continued permanently,`
  line `even though their permanent continuance may not have been expressly provided for when they were`
  line granted.
  line `Prov isions 1 st, 2 nd and 3 rd. — The same as the corresponding Provisions of Rule 2 of this Schedule in`
  line `those cases in which Title Deeds or other Records proving the circumstances of the original grant, or its`
  line `specific recognition by competent authority, are forth coming.`
  line `Provision 4 th. — When there is no proof forthcoming to shew whether or not an Inam, coming under`
  line `the Provisions of this Rule, was granted, or even specifically recognized by a competent authority, still, if`
  line `it has been undisputedly enjoyed for a peri od of forty years before the introduction of the present`
  line `Government, it shall be permanently continued, and enjoyment proved by the mere entry of the Inam, as`
  line `continued in genuine accounts of the District Officers, (even in those not passed by the Governme nt of the`
  line `time being,) is to be considered sufficiently “uninterrupted” to give an Inam the benefit of this provision, if`
  line `there be no entries in the Government accounts which shew that it must have been unauthorized by them.`
  line `Provision 5 th. — If the forthcomi ng records do not go far enough back to test the existence of enjoyment`
  line `of the duration contemplated in Provision 4 th as establishing full prescriptive title in such Inams, still, if so`
  line `far as they do go, they are not opposed to the claimant's assertion th at sufficient enjoyment has taken place,`
  line `the prescriptive title of the Inam shall be admitted according to his assertions, unless there be other evidence`
  line `forthcoming to disprove them.`
  line `Provision 6 th. — The peculiar advantages of this Rule shall not apply to t he holdings of individuals in`
  line `their own names for the performance of ceremonial worship, claims to which must be decided under the`
  line `Rules for personal claims.`
  line `Provision 7 th. — When claims of the denomination coming under this Rule are found to be unsupported`
  line `by proof of original valid title, and are proved void of sufficient prescriptive enjoyment, they are to be`
  line `adjudicated according to Rule 6.`
  line `8. All lands authorizedly held by an official tenure which it is evident from local usage was meant to`
  line `be hereditary, and has been so considered heretofore, even though there be no sunnuds declaring it to be`
  line `so, — for instance, Inams which form the authorized emoluments of any hered itary office, as of Kazees,`
  line `Tillage Joshees, &c., and are not merely personal, — are to be continued permanently.`
  line `Provisions 1 st, 2 nd and 3 rd. — The same as the corresponding Provisions of Rule 2 of this Schedule in`
  line `those cases in which Title Deeds or other Re cords, proving the circumstances of the original grant, or its`
  line `specific recognition by competent authority, are forthcoming,`
  line `Provision 4 th. — When there is no proof forthcoming to shew whether or not an Inam, coming under`
  line `the provisions of this Rule, was gra nted or even specifically recognized by competent authority, still if it`
  line `has been undisputedly enjoyed as an official and not merely personal holding from the earliest period to`
